  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:9-11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 44:9-11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They that make a graven image are vanity ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Hereby discover themselves to be vain, empty, and foolish men. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And their delectable things shall not profit ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Their idols, in which they take so much pleasure. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They are their own witnesses — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They that make them are witnesses against themselves and against their idols, because they know they are not gods, but the work of their own hands. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They see not, nor know",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Have neither sense nor understanding, therefore they have just cause to be ashamed of their folly in worshipping such senseless things. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Who hath formed a god, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — What man in his wits would do it? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Behold, all his fellows shall be ashamed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The workmen who, in this work, are partners with him, by whose cost and command the work is done; or those who any way assist in this work, and join with him in worshipping the image which he makes. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They are of men ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— They are of mankind, and therefore cannot possibly make a god. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They shall be ashamed together ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Though all combine together, they shall be filled with fear and confusion when God shall plead his cause against them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "44:9-20 Image-making is described, to expose the folly of idolaters. Though a man had used part of a log for fuel, he fell down before an image made of the remainder, praying it to deliver him. Man greatly dishonours God, when he represents him after the image of man. Satan blinds the eyes of unbelievers, causing absurd reasonings in matters of religion. Whether men seek happiness in worldly things, or run into unbelief, superstition, or any false system, they feed on ashes. A heart deceived by pride, love of sin, and departure from God, turns men aside from his holy truth and worship. While the affections are depraved, a man holds fast the lie as his best treasure. Are our hearts set upon the wealth of the world and its pleasures? They will certainly prove a lie. If we trust to outward professions and doings, as if those would save us, we deceive ourselves. Self-suspicion is the first step towards self-deliverance. He that would deliver his soul, must question his conscience, Is there not a lie in my right hand?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They that make a graven image - A graven image is one that is cut, or sculptured out of wood or stone, in contradistinction from one that is molten, which is made by being cast. Here it is used to denote an image, or an idol-god in general. God had asserted in the previous verses his own divinity, and he now proceeds to show, at length, the vanity of idols, and of idol-worship. This same topic was introduced in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 40:18-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the notes at that passage), but it is here pursued at greater length, and in a tone and manner far more sarcastic and severe. Perhaps the prophet had two immediate objects in view; first, to reprove the idolatrous spirit in his own time, which prevailed especially in the early part of the reign of Manasseh; and secondly, to show to the exile Jews in Babylon that the gods of the Babylonians could not protect their city, and that Yahweh could rescue his own people. He begins, therefore, by saying, that the makers of the idols were all of them vanity. Of course, the idols themselves could have no more power than their makers, and must be vanity also.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Are all of them vanity - (See the note at Isaiah 41:29).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Are all of them vanity - (See the note at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 41:29",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And their delectable things - Margin, 'Desirable.' The sense is, their valued works, their idol-gods, on which they have lavished so much expense, and which they prize so highly.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Shall not profit - Shall not be able to aid or protect them; shall be of no advantage to them (see Habakkuk 2:18).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Shall not profit - Shall not be able to aid or protect them; shall be of no advantage to them (see ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Habakkuk 2:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And they are their own witnesses - They can foretell nothing; they can furnish no aid; they cannot defend in times of danger. This may refer either to the worshippers, or to the idols themselves - and was alike true of both.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They see not - They have no power of discerning anything. How can they then foresee future events?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That they may be ashamed - The same sentiment is repeated in Isaiah 44:11, and in Isaiah 45:16. The sense is, that shame and confusion must await all who put their trust in an idol-god. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "That they may be ashamed - The same sentiment is repeated in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 44:11",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 45:16",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The sense is, that shame and confusion must await all who put their trust in an idol-god. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "9. (Isa 40:18, 20; 41:29).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "delectable things—the idols in which they take such pride and delight.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "not profit—(Hab 2:18).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "they are their own witnesses—contrasted with, \"Ye are My witnesses\" (Isa 44:8). \"They,\" that is, both the makers and the idols, are witnesses against themselves, for the idols palpably see and know nothing (Ps 115:4-8).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "that they may be ashamed—the consequence deducible from the whole previous argument, not merely from the words immediately preceding, as in Isa 28:13; 36:12. I say all this to show that they are doomed to perish with shame, which is their only fitting end.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
