        "text": "Isaiah 56:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", on the other hand, we have taken it in a different sense). למען implies that the will of the sinner in his sin has also destruction for its object; and this is not something added to the sin, but growing out of it. The question in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " summons the maker of idols for the purpose of announcing his fate, and in הועיל לבלתּי (to no profit) this announcement is already contained. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is simply a development of this expression, \"to no profit.\" יצר, like נטע in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 44:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is contrary to the rhythmical law milra which prevails elsewhere. חבריו (its followers) are not the fellow-workmen of the maker of idols (inasmuch as in that case the maker himself would be left without any share in the threat), but the associates (i.e., followers) of the idols (",
        "children": []
      },
